sols_latex:
Substituting
\emph{y}\textsubscript{0}\textsuperscript{2}=(3\emph{k})\textsuperscript{2},
we find

\begin{align*}
y(t) &= \pm \sqrt{k^2 \pm  |(3k)^2-k^2| e^{-\lambda  t^2}} \\
&= \pm \sqrt{k^2 \pm  8k^2 e^{-\lambda  t^2}} 
\end{align*}

When \emph{t}=0, the argument to the square root is $k^2 \pm 8k^2$,
which must be positive. This indicates that we need to take the positive
branch inside the square root:

\begin{align*}
y(t) = \pm \sqrt{k^2 + 8k^2 e^{-\lambda  t^2}},
\end{align*}

and because \emph{y}(0) \textgreater{} 0, we need to take the positive
branch outside the square root, giving the final answer

\begin{align*}
y(t) &= \sqrt{k^2 + 8k^2 e^{-\lambda  t^2}} \\
 &= |k| \sqrt{1 + 8 e^{-\lambda  t^2}} \\
 &= k \sqrt{1 + 8 e^{-\lambda  t^2}}
\end{align*}

where the last line holds as \emph{k} is positive. As $t \to \infty$ we
have that $y(t) \to +k.$

